Part 5

He left on the sixth morning, the car already loaded, Ramanna hovering near the boot insisting on carrying a bag Vikram was perfectly capable of carrying himself.

The Aghori was waiting by the coffee rows, as if he'd known the exact morning without being told, which perhaps, in his own private accounting, he had.

"Going," the Aghori said. Not a question.

"For now. Land isn't settled. I'll be back and forth for months, maybe longer."

"Land is never really settled. Only borrowed for a while." The Aghori sat on the low wall, unhurried, the way he did everything. "Tell me something before you go. Why this? Liquor. Not medicine, not schools, not something a father could be simply proud of at dinner parties."

Vikram considered lying, the polished answer he gave boardrooms, and found he didn't want to give it here.

"It's not mine to choose," he said. "It was my father's. I never wanted it — not the company, not this business. Twice life put me in it anyway. I'm not chasing money. I stopped believing money was the point a long time ago. I just want to finish what he started, properly, because he can't anymore, and because some part of me still wants to prove I can."

"And the liquor part. Does that trouble you?"

"Yes." Vikram didn't soften it. "I know what it does to some houses. I've read the same reports the Minister's opposition will use against us. I'm not proud of the product. I'm proud, maybe, of doing it honestly where I can — the license clean, the tax paid, the workers looked after. It's not nothing. It's also not everything."

The Aghori looked at him for a long moment, the fire-catch in his eyes replaced now, in daylight, by something quieter.

Then he smiled.

He didn't explain the smile, and Vikram, who had learned by now not to ask, didn't request one.

---

"Here," the Aghori said instead, producing from somewhere in his ash-grey wrap a small folded paper, handed over without ceremony. "Sit like this in the morning, ten minutes, no more. And this word, repeat it when your mind runs too fast for you to catch it. Not for the liquor board. Not for your father. For you, when you're alone and nobody's watching and you still don't know who you're supposed to be that day."

Vikram unfolded it later, in the car, and found a simple seated posture sketched in a shaky hand, and beneath it, one word written twice, the second time underlined.

He didn't ask what it meant.

Some part of him suspected the not-asking was itself the point.

Ramanna knocked on the window as the car began to move, breathless from jogging alongside it the last few steps.

"Sir! Come again for the next wedding, whenever there is one!"

Vikram laughed, properly, and promised he would, and found — a little to his own surprise — that he meant it.
